\begin{document}
\clearpage
\begin{proof}
Below is a simple direct-proof for mathematics 271, taught at the university of Calgary. \newline
\begin{indent}
Suppose we have,
\end{indent}
\begin{align}
x\in\Z 
\end{align}
\begin{indent}
And we intend to make the statement:If $x$ is an even integer, then $x^2$ is even. To first approach the proof for this mathematical statement, we will \emph{suppose} that $x$ is even \emph{and} that it belongs in the integer set. I.e., $x\in\Z$. Getting started with the proof, we can say there exists some $k\in\Z$ for which by the definition of an even integer, $x$ = $2k$. Since we have $x$ = $2k$, 23 can sub this into $x^2$ to get $x^2$ = $(2k)^2$ = $4k^2$ = $2(2k^2)$. Since we previously established that $k\in\Z$, then we have that $x^2$ is in fact even.
\end{indent}

\end{proof}

